ğŸ§© 1. NIST Security MAC â€” Message Authentication Code
Domain: Cryptography / Information Security (NIST = National Institute of Standards and Technology)
Aspect Description
Full name Message Authentication Code
Purpose To verify data integrity and authenticity. Ensures the message was not altered and was created by someone with the shared secret key.
Defined by NIST (e.g., FIPS 198-1, SP 800-38B, etc.)
Mechanism Cryptographic function using a secret key and a message to produce a short tag (MAC).
Algorithms HMAC (Hash-based), CMAC (Block cipher-based), GMAC (Galois/Counter Mode-based)
Key property Depends on a shared secret key â€” only parties knowing the key can verify or create valid MACs.
Used in Secure protocols (TLS, IPsec, SSH), file integrity checking, firmware updates, etc.
Example HMAC-SHA256(message, key) â†’ 32-byte tag
Analogy:
Think of it as a digital wax seal ensuring that a message has not been tampered with and came from the expected sender.
âš™ï¸ 2. Ethernet MAC â€” Media Access Control Address
Domain: Networking / Data Link Layer (IEEE 802.3, OSI Layer 2)
Aspect Description
Full name Media Access Control (Address)
Purpose To uniquely identify a network interface card (NIC) on a local network.
Defined by IEEE (e.g., IEEE 802.3 for Ethernet)
Mechanism A 48-bit (or 64-bit) hardware address assigned to the NIC.
Format Usually written as AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF
Key property Used for frame delivery on the LAN; not secret, just an identifier.
Used in Ethernet, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth (Layer 2 communication)
Example 00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E
Analogy:
Think of it as a postal address that uniquely identifies where to deliver network packets on a local network.
